======================
EEPROM3 Click Board
======================

EEPROM3 click carries Atmel's AT24CM02 DIP-8 socket EEPROM chip with 256 KB of memory. The chip has byte
and page write speeds equal or less than 10 ms. It's specified for a million write cycles, with 100 years
of data retention. The memory, organized as 262144 x 8 bits. The board communicates with the target board
MCU through the mikroBUS I2C interface (SCL, SDA pins) with speeds up to 1 MHz. An onboard jumper allows
you to select the device address (two of them can be connected on the same I2C bus, for a total of 512
KB). The board is designed to use either a 3.3V or a 5V power supply.

=================
Key features
=================
* 256 KB of memory
* I2C interface

==================
INTERFACE SETTINGS
==================
The MCU connects to the I2C pins of the EEPROM3 click board.

Interrupts: Only if drivers configured to use IRQs. 

==================
Clickboard Example
==================

Example writes a single byte of data to the memory and reads back it.

===================
RUNNING THE EXAMPLE
===================

#. Add EEPROM3 click component to the application.
#. Configure dependencies, check default driver assignment 

   * I2C: Add to run example, assign relevant pins.
   * USART: If debug support needed, add to example and assign relevant pins.
   * NOTE: Incase the Click supports only 5v Supply, make sure that it is provided Externally.

#. Configure system drivers: 

   * Enable global interrupts since we are using IRQ's.   
   
#. Export Project: Name and download to relevant IDE. 
#. In Atmel Studio 7: File->Import->Atmel Start Project.
#. In main.c: 
   
   * In main, while(1) loop call: EEPROM3_example()(./examples/src/click_example.c)
   * Add related headerfile:#include<click_example.h>(./examples/include/click_example.h)
   
#. Build and flash into supported evaluation board.
#. Verify the read data using usart print or standard debug methods.
